LOCALITY: Ocean Beach County Park and Santa Ynez River Estuary
Ocean Beach County Park and Santa Ynez River Estuary
TRIP COMMENTS: Canoe trip on the Santa Ynez River Estuary from the beach berm to 13th St. --The purpose of the trip was to check out Red-legged Frog habitat in the upper estuary and especially below the 13th St. bridge where they were found twice in 1993. --Observers: Sue Christopher and Alex Struble and myself. --Weather: overcast, cold, approx. 50°F, storm off coast, surf high. --Conditions: launched canoe from 25th St. at 9 AM headed towards mouth, walked on beach berm just the width of the estuary. Re-embarked for upstream at 10:30 and we were able to reach to about 1/3 mile from 13th St. (farther than I had expected due to due to tremendous water back up. The County Park is closed because the road is flooded.)  One photo is taken looking west in probably not good lighting. From there I walk to to 13th St. in the river bottom, then I returned along the south bank generally about 40 m from the low flow channel walking through the willow riparian. In this eastern most stretch of the river the channel meanders and cuts under willows and some pooling is created. Flow was as it was in previous trips – faster than we would have thought Red-legged Frogs would prefer.  Difficult to tell if the meanders were caused mostly from the deposited settlements or from beaver activity or from deposited vegetation.  No large pile ups of cut vegetation were seen. Generally, approachability to birds was not as close as I had hoped – birds were very skittish from a great distance due to hunting that goes on from the north side of the estuary.  Surprising that so little was heard along the river banks in some sections. The most active area for land birds was from 30 to 130 m below 13th St.   Beaver evidence throughout this section but no dam sites or areas of intense activity were found, even where recent tree cutting by them was noted. Sue is planning a PhD that examines habitat relations of frogs.  Alex is a Brooks Institute photo student producing a video on the Environmental Defense Center and Vertebrate Museum work on shared concerns.  --Surprising in their Absence:--Rails, Falcons, very few vultures seen, Green Heron, Mourning Dove, Loons, Spotted Sandpiper, terns, very few flickers seen. --Other animals: --Fish salvaged: bluegill or sunfish--Deer tracks common--Bobcat seen by Alex where river became uncontrollable--Bullfrogs not heard or seen--Pacific Tree Frogs in several spots.  --[This checklist was input on 18 October 2022 from original notes:  SYRE 21 Jan 94 (stayez14).pdf.  Housed at UCSB's Cheadle Center for Biodiversity and Ecological Restoration.]
With Heather Rottenborn
